Nam matris ferre injurias. ‘⁴ For duty obliges me to bear with the injuries received from my mother.'' This is truly worthy a great and good character, as the poet is solicitous to make that of Pamphilus appear. Compare by all means Cic. Cluent. c. 6. —- 22. Tum uxori obnoxius. “ And then I am under such obligations to my wife.” Obnoxius seems here to import an obligation arising from gratitude. He supposed that either his mother, or wife, was in fault. If his mother, duty obliged him to bear with her3 if his wife, he was under so many obligations to her, for her prudent and discreet behaviour in hiding his faults, that he knew not with what face to show himself disgusted with her.
